{{Short description|None}} [[File:Europe mobile phone penetration map v3.png|thumb|right|350px|Mobile phone penetration in Europe based on available data between 2009 and 2012: {{legend|#9201c1|> 140%}} {{legend|#c66be4|120–140%}} {{legend|#e7b5f8|100–120%}} {{legend|#f4d5fd|< 100%}} {{legend|#bebebe|No data}}]] A [[mobile network operator]] or MNO (also known as a wireless service provider, wireless carrier, cellular company, or mobile network carrier) is a provider of [[wireless communications]] services. The main MNOs in Europe are listed below. == Albania == [[Albania]] as per Q1 2021 has 3.66 million subscribers, out of which there are 2.49 million active users (101% penetration rate). An active user is the number of users that communicated in the last three months.{{cite web|date=2021|title=2021 Q1 report|url=https://www.akep.al/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/Sherbimi-i-telefonise-celulare-perdorues-aktive.pdf|website=AKEP|language=sq}} The regulatory authority for telecommunication in Albania is the [[Electronic and Postal Communications Authority|AKEP]]. In 2022 4iG group, owning ONE Telecommunications, acquires majority stake of [[ALBtelecom Mobile]] ''(80.27%)'' [https://www.4ig.hu/4iG-Acquires-majority-stake-in-leading-albanian-telecommunications-company]. contentMetadata.text: A mobile network operator or MNO (also known as a wireless service provider, wireless carrier, cellular company, or mobile network carrier) is a provider of wireless communications services. The main MNOs in Europe are listed below. Albania as per Q1 2021 has 3.66 million subscribers, out of which there are 2.49 million active users (101% penetration rate). An active user is the number of users that communicated in the last three months. The regulatory authority for telecommunication in Albania is the AKEP. In 2022 4iG group, owning ONE Telecommunications, acquires majority stake of ALBtelecom Mobile (80.27%) [1]. Leading to a network merger on 2023. Andorra has 88,109 mobile subscribers or about 113.63% mobile penetration. As of 2017, Armenia has 3.5 million subscribers in total, and a 120% penetration rate. Austria has 13,0 million assigned numbers (i.e. 2,0 2G, 10,8 3G and 0,1 4G SIM cards), or a 151.0% penetration rate (Q4 2014). The Regulatory Authority for telecommunication in Austria is the Austrian Regulatory Authority for Broadcasting and Telecommunications (RTR). In December 2005, Azerbaijan had 2 million subscribers in total, a 25% penetration rate.[citation needed] In 2014, Azerbaijan has over 10 million subscribers in total and 130% penetration rate.[citation needed] Belarus has 12.0 million subscribers in total, or a 126% penetration rate. (Q4 2020) The Regulatory Authority for telecommunication in Belarus is the Ministry of Communications and Informatization. Belgium has 13.89 million subscribers in total, or a 124% penetration rate (Q4 2014). The Regulatory Authority for telecommunication in Belgium is the Belgian Institute for Postal services and Telecommunications (BIPT). In December 2022, Bosnia and Herzegovina had 3.811 million subscribers in total, or a 115% penetration rate. The Regulatory Authority for telecommunication in Bosnia and Herzegovina is the Communications Regulatory Agency (Regulatorna agencija za komunikacije, RAK). Bulgaria has 7 964 361 subscribers in total, or a 123,5% penetration rate according to the CRC annual report for 2022. The Regulatory Authority for Telecommunication in Bulgaria is the Communications Regulation Commission (CRC). Croatia has 4,404,652 subscribers in total, or a 102,8% penetration rate. (4Q 2019) The Regulatory Authority for telecommunication in Croatia is the Hrvatska agencija za poštu i elektronicke komunikacije (website available in Croatian and English language). Cyprus has 1.392.480 subscribers in total, or a 151.7% penetration rate (excludes Northern Cyprus). The Regulatory Authority for telecommunication in Cyprus (excluding Northern Cyprus) is OCECPR (Office of the Commissioner of Electronic Communications and Postal Regulation). The Czech Republic has 16.121 million subscribers in total, or a 151% penetration rate (December 2019). The Regulatory Authority for telecommunication in the Czech Republic is the Český telekomunikační úřad. Denmark has 8.208 million subscribers in total, or a 146% penetration rate (June 2014). The regulator is the Danish Business Authority. Estonia has 2.524 million subscribers in total, or a 188% penetration rate. (December 2008) The Faroe Islands have 0.059 million subscribers in total (exact number 61,388), or a 126% penetration rate (population 48,652). (2020) The Regulatory Authority for telecommunication in the Faroe Islands is Fjarskiftiseftirlitið. Finland has 7.700 million subscribers in total, or a 144.59% penetration rate. (December 2009). France has 75.5 million subscribers in total, or a 115.2% penetration rate (September 2015). The Regulatory Authority for telecommunication in France is ARCEP. As of March 2023, Georgia has 5,369,908 subscribers in total. The Regulatory Authority for telecommunication in Georgia is the Georgian National Communications Commission. Germany has 114.1 million subscribers in total, or a 140% penetration rate (December 2011). The Regulatory Authority for telecommunication in Germany is the Bundesnetzagentur (BNetzA). Gibraltar, the British overseas territory has 0.028 million subscribers in total, or a 92.12% penetration rate. (December 2009) In 2020, Greece had 11,412,995 subscribers in total, or 109% subscriptions per 100 inhabitants. The Regulatory Authority for telecommunications in Greece is the Hellenic Telecommunications and Post Commission (EETT). The British Crown dependency Guernsey has 0.055 million subscribers in total, or a 95% penetration rate.[citation needed] (December 2005) Hungary has 11.8 million subscribers in total. (December 2017) The Regulatory Authority for telecommunication in Hungary is NMHH – Nemzeti Média-, és Hírközlési Hatóság. *900 MHz 3G closed in 07.2022, in process of shutting down 2100 MHz, complete shutdown expected in 2023 Iceland has 0.470 million subscribers in total, or a 129.19% penetration rate. (July 2019) The Regulatory Authority for telecommunication in Iceland is Póst- og fjarskiptastofnun. At the end of March 2022 Ireland had 8.117 million mobile subscribers in total, representing a 158.4% penetration rate. If mobile broadband and M2M subscriptions are excluded, the total number of mobile subscribers was 5.414 million, representing a 105.6% penetration rate. The Regulatory Authority for telecommunication in Ireland is the Commission for Communications Regulation (ComReg). The British Crown dependency Isle of Man has an unknown number of subscribers in total and an unknown percentage penetration rate. As of March 2022, Italy has 106.5 million active lines in total, of whose 78 million are human ones, or a 174% penetration rate. The country's telecom regulator is AGCOM. In 2016 Wind and 3 Italy have agreed to complete a merger that has been approved by European and national authorities and, since March 2020, all consumer and business offers are sold under the new brand Wind Tre. A new operator, Iliad, entered the Italian market in May 2018 as a consequence of this merger. Kosovo has 1.88 million subscribers in total, or a 103.47% penetration rate (June 2018). As of February 2023, Vala and Ipko have been awarded with 5G licenses and is currently under deployment. Latvia has 2.243 million subscribers in total, or a 99.72% penetration rate. (December 2009) Liechtenstein has 0.039 million subscribers in total, or a 105% penetration rate. (April 2015) The Liechtenstein mobile phone system is attached to Switzerland, customers of these three providers can roam on Swiss networks without additional fees. Lithuania has 4.941 million subscribers in total, or a 167% penetration rate (25 October 2013). The regulator is Ryšių Reguliavimo Tarnyba (RRT). Luxembourg has 719,000 subscribers in total, or a 148% penetration rate. (December 2009) Malta has 0.702 million subscribers in total, or a 130.19% penetration rate (June 2023) Moldova has 4.263 million subscribers in total, or a 120% penetration rate (2012). The country's telecommunications regulator is ANRCETI. Monaco has 0.023 million subscribers on the Monaco Telecom network, or a 70.1% penetration rate (December 2009). The French networks are also widely available in Monaco, but they don't disclose subscriber figures for Monaco. Montenegro has 1.097.574 subscribers in total, or a 177.02% penetration rate (October 2013). The Regulatory Authority for telecommunication in Montenegro is Agencija za elektronske komunikacije i poštansku djelatnost. The Netherlands has 22.12 million subscribers in total, or a 125.7% penetration rate (Q1 2023). The Regulatory Authorities for telecommunication in The Netherlands are the Netherlands Authority for Consumers and Markets (ACM: Autoriteit Consument & Markt) and the Dutch Authority for Digital Infrastructure (RDI: Rijksdienst Digitale Infrastructuur) North Macedonia has 2.299 million subscribers in total, or a 105% penetration rate. The Regulatory Authority for telecommunication in North Macedonia is AEK. Norway has 5.730 million subscribers in total, or a 108.97% penetration rate (December 2016). The regulatory authority for telecommunication in Norway is the Norwegian Post and Telecommunications Authority. Poland has 54.1 million subscribers in total (Q4 2020). The country's telecom regulator is UKE (Urząd Komunikacji Elektronicznej). Portugal has 17.6 million subscribers in total, or a 170.5% penetration rate (13.1 million active subscribers or 127.4% penetration rate). (Q3 2017) The country's telecom regulator is ANACOM. Romania has 23.2 million active subscribers in total, or a 122% penetration rate. (2022) The country's telcom regulator is ANCOM. The country's telecom regulator is Roskomnadzor. San Marino has 0.037 million subscribers in total, or a 116.95% penetration rate. (December 2013) Serbia has 9.1987 million subscribers based on the 3-month customer activity, or a 128.09% penetration rate. (December 2013) The Regulatory Authority for telecommunication in Serbia is RATEL (Regulatorna agencija za elektronske komunikacije i poštanske usluge). Slovakia has 7,68 million subscribers in total, or a 132.79% penetration rate. All facts are based on the 3-month customer activity base. (November 2019) The Regulatory Authority for electronic communications "telecommunication" in Slovakia is Úrad pre reguláciu elektronických komunikácií a poštových služieb (RÚ). Slovenia has 2.697.932 subscribers in total, or a 127% penetration rate. (2Q 2023) The Regulatory Authority for telecommunication in Slovenia is AKOS (Agencija za komunikacijska omrežja in storitve). Spain has 57.866 million subscribers in total, or a 122.00% penetration rate. (Mar 2023) The Regulatory Authority for telecommunication in Spain is CNMC (Comisión Nacional de los Mercados y la Competencia). Note: The number of subscribers of each operator includes the subscribers of the main brand and the rest of its brands and subsidiaries. Sweden has 14.244 million subscribers in total, or a 148.4% penetration rate (2013) The country's telcom regulator is Swedish Post and Telecom Authority. Switzerland has 11.365 million mobile subscribers and a 138% penetration rate. (December 2014) The country's telecom regulator is BAKOM. Turkey has 91.3 million subscribers in total, or a 107.1% penetration rate. (Q2 2023) The telecom regulator in Turkey is Information and Communication Technologies Authority (BTK : Bilgi Teknolojileri ve İletişim Kurumu). Ukraine has 55.860 million subscribers in total, or a 129.8% penetration rate. (October, 2018) The country's telecom regulator is NKRZI. *Due to the Russian-Ukrainian war the national roaming among other operators is free and it includes: voice calls, SMS and mobile 2G / 3G Internet at speeds up to 512 kbit/s. The United Kingdom has 92.0 million subscribers in total, or an approximate 139% penetration rate (31 December 2017). The country's telecom regulator is Ofcom. texts.title: Albania
texts.value:
[[Albania]] as per Q1 2021 has 3.66 million subscribers, out of which there are 2.49 million active users (101% penetration rate). An active user is the number of users that communicated in the last three months.<ref>{{cite web|date=2021|title=2021 Q1 report|url=https://www.akep.al/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/Sherbimi-i-telefonise-celulare-perdorues-aktive.pdf|website=AKEP|language=sq}}</ref>

The regulatory authority for telecommunication in Albania is the [[Electronic and Postal Communications Authority|AKEP]].

In 2022 4iG group, owning ONE Telecommunications, acquires majority stake of [[ALBtelecom Mobile]] (80.27%) . Leading to a network merger on 2023.

texts.title: Andorra
texts.value: [[Andorra]] has 88,109 mobile subscribers<ref name="cia-world-factbook">{{cite web | url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2151.html | title=Central Intelligence Agency | publisher=Cia.gov | access-date=9 December 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121119041944/https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2151.html | archive-date=19 November 2012 | url-status=dead | df=dmy-all }}</ref> or about 113.63% mobile penetration.

texts.title: Armenia
texts.value: As of 2017, [[Armenia]] has 3.5 million subscribers in total, and a 120% penetration rate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/the-world-factbook/countries/armenia/|title=Middle East :: Armenia — The World Factbook - Central Intelligence Agency|website=www.cia.gov|access-date=29 October 2020}}</ref>

texts.title: Austria
texts.value:
[[Austria]] has 13,0 million assigned numbers (i.e. 2,0 2G, 10,8 3G and 0,1 4G SIM cards), or a 151.0% penetration rate (Q4 2014<ref name="rtr.at">{{cite web | date=30 June 2015 | publisher=RTR-GmbH | title=RTR Telekom Monitor Jahresbericht 2014 | url=https://www.rtr.at/de/inf/TKMonitor_2014/TM_Jahresbericht_2014.pdf | language=de | pages=8, 17, 20 | access-date=7 November 2015}}</ref>).

The Regulatory Authority for telecommunication in Austria is the Austrian Regulatory Authority for Broadcasting and Telecommunications (RTR).

texts.title: Azerbaijan
texts.value: In December 2005, [[Azerbaijan]] had 2 million subscribers in total, a 25% penetration rate.{{Citation needed|date=November 2007}} In 2014, [[Azerbaijan]] has over 10 million subscribers in total and 130% penetration rate.{{citation needed|date=August 2022}}

texts.title: Belarus
texts.value:
[[Belarus]] has 12.0 million subscribers in total, or a 126% penetration rate. (Q4 2020)

The Regulatory Authority for telecommunication in Belarus is the Ministry of Communications and Informatization.

texts.title: Belgium
texts.value:
[[Belgium]] has 13.89 million subscribers in total, or a 124% penetration rate<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.bipt.be/public/files/fr/21529/Situation_du_secteur_des_communications_électroniques_2014.pdf|date=17 July 2015|title=Situation du secteur des communications electroniques}}</ref> (Q4 2014).

The Regulatory Authority for telecommunication in Belgium is the Belgian Institute for Postal services and Telecommunications (BIPT).

texts.title: Bosnia and Herzegovina
texts.value:
In December 2022, [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] had 3.811 million subscribers in total,<ref name="U šta telekomi ulažu sredstva od naplate 1 KM?">{{cite book|url=https://tip.ba/2023/07/20/u-sta-telekomi-ulazu-sredstva-od-naplate-naknade-u-iznosu-od-1-km/|title=U šta telekomi ulažu sredstva od naplate 1 KM?}}</ref> or a {{Percentage|3811931|3318407}} penetration rate.

The Regulatory Authority for telecommunication in Bosnia and Herzegovina is the Communications Regulatory Agency (Regulatorna agencija za komunikacije, RAK).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rak.ba/bos/|title=Regulatorna agencija za komunikacije|website=rak.ba|language=bs|access-date=19 February 2018}}</ref>

texts.title: Bulgaria
texts.value:
[[Bulgaria]] has 7 964 361 subscribers in total, or a 123,5% penetration rate according to the CRC annual report for 2022.<ref name="autogenerated1">{{cite web|url=https://crc.bg/files/Годишен_доклад_на_Комисията_за_регулиране_на_съобщенията_за_2022_г._1_fin1.pdf|title=CRC yearly report 2022|website=crc.bg|publisher=CRC|access-date=1 July 2022}}</ref>
 
The Regulatory Authority for Telecommunication in Bulgaria is the Communications Regulation Commission (CRC).

texts.title: Croatia
texts.value:
[[Croatia]] has 4,404,652 subscribers in total, or a 102,8% penetration rate. (4Q 2019)<ref>{{cite web | publisher=HAKOM.hr | title=Hakom Mobile Report Q4 2017 | url=http://www.hakom.hr/UserDocsImages/2015/e_trziste/Croatian%20Quarterly%20electronic%20communications%20data,%20Q22015.pdf | access-date=7 November 2015 }}</ref>

The Regulatory Authority for telecommunication in Croatia is the Hrvatska agencija za poštu i elektronicke komunikacije (website available in Croatian and English language).

texts.title: Cyprus
texts.value:
[[Cyprus]] has 1.392.480 subscribers in total, or a 151.7% penetration rate (excludes Northern Cyprus).<ref name="Rizzo">{{cite web |url=https://cablenet.com.cy/wp-content/uploads/Cablenet_-FAS-2023.pdf |title=FAS 2023 |pages=10–11 |date=May 2023 |publisher=Rizzo Farrugia Investment Consultants|access-date=27 August 2023}}</ref>

The Regulatory Authority for telecommunication in Cyprus (excluding  Northern Cyprus) is OCECPR (Office of the Commissioner of Electronic Communications and Postal Regulation).

texts.title: Czechia
texts.value:
The [[Czech Republic]] has 16.121 million subscribers in total, or a 151% penetration rate (December 2019).<ref name="ctu">{{cite web | title=The Annual Report of the Czech Telecommunication Office for 2011 | url=http://www.ctu.eu/164/download/Annual_Reports/annual_report-2011.pdf | publisher=Czech Telecommunication Office | access-date=13 December 2012 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140811112656/http://www.ctu.eu/164/download/Annual_Reports/annual_report-2011.pdf | archive-date=11 August 2014 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>

The Regulatory Authority for telecommunication in the Czech Republic is the Český telekomunikační úřad.

texts.title: Denmark
texts.value: [[Denmark]] has 8.208 million subscribers in total, or a 146% penetration rate<ref>{{cite web| format=XLS| publisher=erhvervsstyrelsen.dk| title=Telecom Statistics – 1st half 2014 – Main Tables| url=http://erhvervsstyrelsen.dk/file/525102/hovedtal-baggrundsark-1H14-xls.xls| access-date=15 January 2015}}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> (June 2014). The regulator is the Danish Business Authority.

texts.title: Estonia
texts.value: [[Estonia]] has 2.524 million subscribers in total, or a 188% penetration rate.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.itu.int/ITU-D/icteye/Reporting/ShowReportFrame.aspx?ReportName=/WTI/CellularSubscribersPublic&RP_intYear=2008&RP_intLanguageID=1 | title=International Telecommunication Union – BDT | publisher=ITU.int | access-date=9 October 2012}}</ref> (December 2008)

texts.title: Faroe Islands
texts.value: The [[Faroe Islands]] have 0.059 million subscribers in total (exact number 61,388), or a 126% penetration rate (population 48,652).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://vs.cdn.fo/savn/2714/2020.pdf?s=snCPjOA1LL9RE-R2tYw3J_LQjI8|title=Telecom Statistics|date=28 August 2021}}</ref> (2020) The Regulatory Authority for telecommunication in the Faroe Islands is Fjarskiftiseftirlitið.

texts.title: Finland
texts.value: [[Finland]] has 7.700 million subscribers in total, or a 144.59% penetration rate.<ref name="autogenerated1" /> (December 2009).

texts.title: France
texts.value:
France has 75.5 million subscribers in total, or a 115.2% penetration rate (September 2015).<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.arcep.fr/index.php?id=12168 | title=Observatoire des marchés des communications électroniques en France – Observatoire des investissements et de l'emploi – 3ème trimestre 2013 – résultats définitifs (9 janvier 2014) | publisher=Arcep.fr | date=9 January 2014 }}</ref>

The Regulatory Authority for telecommunication in France is [[Autorité de Régulation des Communications Électroniques, des Postes et de la Distribution de la Presse|ARCEP]].

texts.title: Georgia
texts.value: As of March 2023, [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] has 5,369,908 subscribers in total. The Regulatory Authority for telecommunication in Georgia is the [[Georgian National Communications Commission]].<ref>Georgia. [[The World Factbook]]. [[Central Intelligence Agency]].</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://analytics.comcom.ge/en/statistics/?c=mobiles&sid=1109562|title=Mobile • Subscribers by companies}}</ref>

texts.title: Germany
texts.value:
Germany has 114.1 million subscribers in total, or a 140% penetration rate<ref name="autogenerated1" /> (December 2011).
The Regulatory Authority for telecommunication in Germany is the [[Federal Network Agency|Bundesnetzagentur (BNetzA)]].

texts.title: Gibraltar
texts.value: [[Gibraltar]], the British overseas territory has 0.028 million subscribers in total, or a 92.12% penetration rate.<ref name="autogenerated1" /> (December 2009)

texts.title: Greece
texts.value: In [[2020]], [[Greece]] had 11,412,995 subscribers in total, or 109% subscriptions per 100 inhabitants.<ref>{{Citation |title=Greece |date=2023-01-23 |url=https://www.cia.gov/the-world-factbook/countries/greece/#communications |work=The World Factbook |publisher=Central Intelligence Agency |language=en |access-date=2023-01-31}}</ref> The Regulatory Authority for telecommunications in Greece is the [[Hellenic Telecommunications and Post Commission|Hellenic Telecommunications and Post Commission (EETT)]].

texts.title: Guernsey
texts.value: The British Crown dependency [[Guernsey]] has 0.055 million subscribers in total, or a 95% penetration rate. {{Citation needed|date=November 2007}} (December 2005)

texts.title: Hungary
texts.value:
[[Hungary]] has 11.8 million subscribers in total.<ref>{{cite web |date= March 2018| publisher=KSH.hu | title=Távközlés, internet, televíziószolgáltatás, 2017. IV. negyedév | url=https://www.ksh.hu/docs/hun/xftp/gyor/tav/tav1712.pdf }}</ref> (December 2017)

The Regulatory Authority for telecommunication in Hungary is NMHH – Nemzeti Média-, és Hírközlési Hatóság.

<nowiki>*</nowiki>900 MHz 3G closed in 07.2022, in process of shutting down 2100 MHz, complete shutdown expected in 2023

texts.title: Iceland
texts.value:
[[Iceland]] has 0.470 million subscribers in total, or a 129.19% penetration rate.<ref name="autogenerated1" /> (July 2019)

The Regulatory Authority for telecommunication in Iceland is Póst- og fjarskiptastofnun.

texts.title: Ireland
texts.value:
At the end of March 2022 Ireland had 8.117 million mobile subscribers in total, representing a 158.4% penetration rate.

If mobile broadband and M2M subscriptions are excluded, the total number of mobile subscribers was 5.414 million, representing a 105.6% penetration rate.<ref>{{cite web | publisher=ComReg | title=Quarterly Key Data Report Q1 2022 | date=9 June 2022 | url=https://www.comreg.ie/publication/quarterly-key-data-report-q1-2022 }}</ref>

The Regulatory Authority for telecommunication in Ireland is the [[Commission for Communications Regulation]] (ComReg).

texts.title: Isle of Man
texts.value: The British [[Crown dependency]] [[Isle of Man]] has an unknown number of subscribers in total and an unknown percentage penetration rate.

texts.title: Italy
texts.value:
As of March 2022, Italy has 106.5 million active lines in total, of whose 78 million are human ones, or a 174% penetration rate.<ref name="agcom">{{cite web|url=https://www.agcom.it/documents/10179/5789992/Allegato+15-7-2022/638080c9-de74-4166-b674-f1ef7c2d9cae?version=1.0|title=Osservatorio sulle comunicazioni|publisher=[[Autorità per le Garanzie nelle Comunicazioni|AGCOM]]|language=it|access-date=4 August 2022}}</ref> The country's telecom regulator is [[Autorità per le Garanzie nelle Comunicazioni|AGCOM]].

In 2016 [[WIND (Italy)|Wind]] and [[3 Italy]] have agreed to complete a merger that has been approved by European and national authorities and, since March 2020, all consumer and business offers are sold under the new brand [[Wind Tre]]. A new operator, [[Iliad Italia|Iliad]], entered the Italian market in May 2018 as a consequence of this merger.<ref>{{cite news|title=Fitch: Prospects of Wind/H3G Merger Approval Improved by Iliad Deal|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSFit966462|work=Reuters|date=6 July 2016}}</ref>

texts.title: Kosovo
texts.value: [[Kosovo]] has 1.88 million subscribers in total, or a 103.47% penetration rate<ref name="budde">{{cite web | url=http://www.budde.com.au/Research/Kosovo-Telecoms-Mobile-Broadband-and-Digital-Media-Statistics-and-Analyses.html | title=Kosovo – Telecoms, Mobile, Broadband and Digital Media – Statistics and Analyses | publisher=Budde }}</ref> (June 2018). As of February 2023, Vala and Ipko have been awarded with 5G licenses and is currently under deployment.<ref>{{Cite web |title= |url=https://www.datacenterdynamics.com/en/news/kosovo-awards-5g-licenses-to-ipko-and-telecom-kosovo/}}</ref>

texts.title: Latvia
texts.value: [[Latvia]] has 2.243 million subscribers in total, or a 99.72% penetration rate.<ref name="autogenerated1" /> (December 2009)

texts.title: Liechtenstein
texts.value:
[[Liechtenstein]] has 0.039 million subscribers in total, or a 105% penetration rate.<ref name="autogenerated1" /> (April 2015)


The Liechtenstein mobile phone system is attached to Switzerland, customers of these three providers can roam on Swiss networks without additional fees.

texts.title: Lithuania
texts.value:
[[Lithuania]] has 4.941 million subscribers in total, or a 167% penetration rate (25 October 2013).<ref name="rrt">{{cite web | title=Report on the electronic communications sector | url=http://www.rrt.lt/download/17804/report%202013%20iiq.pdf | publisher=Communications Regulatory Authority of the Republic of Lithuania | access-date=25 October 2013}}</ref>

The regulator is Ryšių Reguliavimo Tarnyba (RRT).

texts.title: Luxembourg
texts.value: [[Luxembourg]] has 719,000 subscribers in total, or a 148% penetration rate.<ref name="autogenerated1" /> (December 2009)

texts.title: Malta
texts.value: [[Malta]] has 0.702 million subscribers in total, or a 130.19% penetration rate<ref name="MCA Q4 2022">{{cite web|title=MCA Statistics Q4 2022|url=https://www.mca.org.mt/sites/default/files/DRS%20as%20at%20Q4%202022.xlsx|work=Malta Communications Authority|access-date=8 June 2023|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140318020102/http://www.mca.org.mt/statistics/key-market-indicators-electronic-communications-and-post-q1-2009-q4-2013|archive-date=18 March 2014}}</ref> (June 2023)

texts.title: Moldova
texts.value:
[[Moldova]] has 4.263 million subscribers in total, or a 120% penetration rate<ref>{{cite web | publisher=anrceti.md | title=anrceti | url=http://anrceti.md/telmob#fig4 }}</ref> (2012).

The country's telecommunications regulator is ANRCETI.

texts.title: Monaco
texts.value: [[Monaco]] has 0.023 million subscribers on the [[Monaco Telecom]] network, or a 70.1% penetration rate<ref name="autogenerated1" /> (December 2009). The French networks are also widely available in Monaco, but they don't disclose subscriber figures for Monaco.

texts.title: Montenegro
texts.value:
[[Montenegro]] has 1.097.574 subscribers in total, or a 177.02% penetration rate (October 2013).<ref>{{cite web | publisher=Agencija za elektronske komunikacije i poštansku djelatnost | title=Informacija o stanju tržišta elektronskih komunikacija za oktobar 2013. godine – mobilna telefonija | url=http://www.ekip.me/download/Mobilna%20-%20oktobar.pdf | access-date=29 May 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131216045755/http://www.ekip.me/download/Mobilna%20-%20oktobar.pdf | archive-date=16 December 2013 | url-status=dead | df=dmy-all }}</ref>

The Regulatory Authority for telecommunication in Montenegro is Agencija za elektronske komunikacije i poštansku djelatnost.

texts.title: Netherlands
texts.value:
The [[Netherlands]] has 22.12 million subscribers in total, or a 125.7% penetration rate<ref>{{cite web |url=https://datareportal.com/reports/digital-2023-netherlands |title=Digital 2023: The Netherlands |date=9 February 2023 |website=DataReportal.com|access-date=30 August 2023}}</ref> (Q1 2023).

The Regulatory Authorities for telecommunication in The Netherlands are the [[Netherlands Authority for Consumers and Markets]] (ACM: Autoriteit Consument & Markt) and the Dutch Authority for Digital Infrastructure (RDI: Rijksdienst Digitale Infrastructuur)

texts.title: North Macedonia
texts.value:
[[North Macedonia]] has 2.299 million subscribers in total, or a 105% penetration rate.<ref name="AEKQuarterly">{{cite web | url=http://www.aec.mk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=689%3A------------2012-&catid=54%3A2011-06-22-08-36-12&Itemid=123&lang=mk | title=Report on the development of the electronic communication market for Q3 2012 | access-date=14 March 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130605153248/http://www.aec.mk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=689%3A------------2012-&catid=54%3A2011-06-22-08-36-12&Itemid=123&lang=mk | archive-date=5 June 2013 | url-status=dead | df=dmy-all }}</ref>

The Regulatory Authority for telecommunication in North Macedonia is AEK.

texts.title: Norway
texts.value:
[[Norway]] has 5.730 million subscribers in total, or a 108.97% penetration rate<ref name="autogenerated1" /> (December 2016).

The regulatory authority for telecommunication in Norway is the [[Norwegian Post and Telecommunications Authority]].

texts.title: Poland
texts.value:
[[Poland]] has 54.1 million subscribers in total (Q4 2020).<ref>{{cite web | title=Raport o stanie rynku telekomunikacyjnego w 2020 roku | url=https://www.uke.gov.pl/akt/raport-o-stanie-rynku-telekomunikacyjnego-w-2020-r-,391.html | date=30 June 2021 | publisher=UKE|access-date=16 January 2022}}</ref>

The country's telecom regulator is UKE (Urząd Komunikacji Elektronicznej).

texts.title: Portugal
texts.value:
[[Portugal]] has 17.6 million subscribers in total, or a 170.5% penetration rate (13.1 million active subscribers or 127.4% penetration rate).<ref name="anacom">{{cite web | format=PDF | publisher=anacom.pt | title=anacom | url=http://www.anacom.pt/render.jsp?contentId=1372777 | access-date=9 March 2018 }}</ref> (Q3 2017)

The country's telecom regulator is [[ANACOM]].

texts.title: Romania
texts.value:
[[Romania]] has 23.2 million active subscribers in total, or a 122% penetration rate. (2022)<ref>{{Cite web|title=Annual reports|url=https://www.ancom.ro/rapoarte-anuale_268|publisher=ANCOM|language=en}}</ref>
The country's telcom regulator is ANCOM.

texts.title: Russia
texts.value: The country's telecom regulator is [[Federal Service for Supervision of Communications, Information Technology and Mass Media|Roskomnadzor]].

texts.title: San Marino
texts.value: [[San Marino]] has 0.037 million subscribers in total, or a 116.95% penetration rate.<ref name="autogenerated1" /> (December 2013)

texts.title: Serbia
texts.value:
[[Serbia]] has 9.1987 million subscribers based on the 3-month customer activity, or a 128.09% penetration rate.<ref>{{cite web | publisher=ratel.rs | title=RATEL Press report May 2014 | url=http://www.ratel.rs/upload/documents/Pregled_trzista/Ratel%20Pregled%20trzista%202014.pdf }}</ref> (December 2013)

The Regulatory Authority for telecommunication in Serbia is RATEL (Regulatorna agencija za elektronske komunikacije i poštanske usluge).

texts.title: Slovakia
texts.value:
[[Slovakia]] has 7,68 million subscribers in total, or a 132.79% penetration rate. All facts are based on the 3-month customer activity base.<ref name="itnews.sk">{{cite web|url=https://zive.aktuality.sk/clanok/143290/slovaci-za-polroka-prevolali-miliardy-minut-vacsina-ludi-ma-pausal/|title=Slováci za polroka prevolali miliardy minút. Väčšina ľudí má paušál|work=zive.aktuality.sk}}</ref> (November 2019)

The Regulatory Authority for electronic communications "telecommunication" in Slovakia is Úrad pre reguláciu elektronických komunikácií a poštových služieb (RÚ).

texts.title: Slovenia
texts.value:
[[Slovenia]] has 2.697.932 subscribers in total, or a 127% penetration rate.<ref>Agencija za komunikacijska omrežja in storitve Republike Slovenije</ref> (2Q 2023)

The Regulatory Authority for telecommunication in Slovenia is AKOS (Agencija za komunikacijska omrežja in storitve).

texts.title: Spain
texts.value:
{{See also|List of telephone operating companies#Spain}}

Spain has 57.866 million subscribers in total, or a 122.00% penetration rate. (Mar 2023)<ref name="CNMCData - Informe Mensual">{{Cite web |title=CNMC Data |url=https://data.cnmc.es/telecomunicaciones-y-sector-audiovisual/conjuntos-de-datos/datos-mensuales/telecomunicaciones |access-date=2023-05-22 |website=data.cnmc.es}}</ref>

The Regulatory Authority for telecommunication in Spain is [[Comisión Nacional de los Mercados y la Competencia|CNMC]] (Comisión Nacional de los Mercados y la Competencia).<small></small>

Note: The number of subscribers of each operator includes the subscribers of the main brand and the rest of its brands and subsidiaries.

texts.title: Sweden
texts.value:
[[Sweden]] has 14.244 million subscribers in total, or a 148.4% penetration rate<ref name="autogenerated1" /> (2013)

The country's telcom regulator is [[Swedish Post and Telecom Authority]].

texts.title: Switzerland
texts.value:
[[Switzerland]] has 11.365{{cite web|url=https://www.bakom.admin.ch/bakom/de/home/telekommunikation/zahlen-und-fakten/sammlung-statisticher-daten/mobilfunk/anzahl-mobilfunkkundinnen-und-kunden.html|title=Anzahl Mobilfunkkundinnen und -kunden|first=Bundesamt für Kommunikation|last=BAKOM|website=www.bakom.admin.ch}} million mobile subscribers and a 138% penetration rate. (December 2014)
The country's telecom regulator is BAKOM.

texts.title: Turkey
Ukraine
texts.value:
[[Ukraine]] has 55.860 million subscribers in total, or a 129.8% penetration rate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nkrzi.gov.ua/index.php?r=site/index&pg=149&language=uk|title=Національна комісія, що здійснює державне регулювання у сфері зв'язку та інформатизації|Рухомий (мобільний) зв'язок|website=nkrzi.gov.ua}}</ref> (October, 2018)

The country's telecom regulator is NKRZI.

<nowiki>*</nowiki>Due to the Russian-Ukrainian war the national roaming among other operators is free and it includes: voice calls, SMS and mobile 2G / 3G Internet at speeds up to 512 kbit/s.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Visit Ukraine - INFORMATION PAGE FOR FOREIGN TOURISTS |url=https://visitukraine.today/ |access-date=2022-03-20 |website=visitukraine.today}}</ref>
